{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17659034","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17659034"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T23:00:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T23:00:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20844"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20844","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20844"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13719"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96416"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13719","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13719"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20844"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79065"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11597"},{"type":"tags","id":"12331"},{"type":"tags","id":"12668"},{"type":"tags","id":"12669"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"33030"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33031"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96416","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96416"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes a key mechanism in cancer cell invasion of the extracellular matrix?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Decreased expression of integrins on tumour cell surfaces","Degradation of basement membrane by matrix metalloproteinases","Increased expression of E-cadherin on tumour cell surfaces","Inhibition of epithelial-mesenchymal transition","Reduced secretion of autocrine motility factors"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is \u003Cstrong\u003Edegradation of basement membrane by matrix metalloproteinases\u003C/strong\u003E. Matrix metalloproteinases (MMPs) are proteolytic enzymes that play a crucial role in cancer invasion by degrading basement membrane and interstitial connective tissue components. MMPs, particularly MMP-9, cleave type IV collagen in basement membranes, creating pathways for cancer cell migration. Additionally, MMPs release growth factors sequestered in the ECM and generate cleavage products with chemotactic and angiogenic properties. Malignant tumours typically show higher MMP expression than their benign counterparts.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased expression of E-cadherin on tumour cell surfaces\u003C/strong\u003E - This is incorrect because cancer invasion typically involves decreased, not increased, E-cadherin expression. E-cadherin mediates cell-cell adhesion, and its loss (through mutation or epithelial-mesenchymal transition) allows cancer cells to detach from one another, which is the first step in invasion.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased expression of integrins on tumour cell surfaces\u003C/strong\u003E - This is incorrect because cancer cells typically show complex changes in integrin expression rather than simple downregulation. They often express different integrins that promote survival when detached from the normal ECM (resistance to anoikis) and facilitate attachment to modified ECM components.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibition of epithelial-mesenchymal transition\u003C/strong\u003E - This is incorrect because epithelial-mesenchymal transition (EMT) promotes, rather than inhibits, cancer invasion. During EMT, epithelial markers like E-cadherin are downregulated while mesenchymal markers are upregulated, conferring a pro-migratory phenotype that facilitates metastasis.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReduced secretion of autocrine motility factors\u003C/strong\u003E - This is incorrect because increased, not reduced, secretion of autocrine motility factors (including chemokines and growth factors) stimulates and directs cancer cell movement through degraded ECM during invasion.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECancer invasion is a multistep process involving: (1) loosening of tumour cell-cell interactions, (2) degradation of ECM, (3) attachment to remodelled ECM components, and (4) migration of tumour cells. MMPs are central to the second step of this process.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Invasion of the extracellular matrix (ECM) by cancer cells is an active process involving dissociation of cell-cell interactions, ECM degradation, altered attachment to ECM, and cell migration.","E-cadherin loss through mutation or epithelial-mesenchymal transition (EMT) is a key mechanism that reduces cell-cell adhesion in cancer cells.","Matrix metalloproteinases (MMPs) play a crucial role in degrading basement membrane and interstitial connective tissue during cancer invasion.","Changes in integrin expression allow cancer cells to alter their attachment to ECM components and resist anoikis (detachment-induced cell death)."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 7; pages 307-308."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79065"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20844"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79065","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79065"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-01T11:28:08+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-01T11:28:31+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13719"}},"content":{"data":{"